<li>
<p>
  Consider the spring-mass system shown below.
  Here, an object of mass <m>m</m> is attached to a spring which exerts a linear restorative force with spring constant <m>k</m>.
  Assume also a damping coefficient <m>c</m> (perhaps due to friction).
  Then, if <m>x</m> denotes the displacement from equilibrium <m>x=0</m>, we have
</p>
<men xml:id="dashpoteqn">
  m\frac{d^{2}x}{dt^{2}}+ c\frac{dx}{dt}+ kx = 0.
</men>

<figure xml:id="SpringMass4" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <caption>A dashpot.</caption>
<image source="SpringMass4.jpg" width="50%">
  <description>A mass–spring–dashpot system: a wall on the left is connected to a zig‑zag spring, 
    which is attached to a rectangular block labeled “m”; on the right side of the block a rod 
    connects to a dashpot (damper) attached to another wall. </description>
</image>
</figure>

  <p>
    Note: A <term>dashpot</term> is a device (like a shock absorber) designed to exert a resistive force 
    proportional to the velocity of the object.
    We study the different types of solutions which depend on the values of <m>m, k</m>, and <m>c</m>.
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        <alert>Undamped Motion.</alert> Suppose there is no friction or other damping factors 
        (i.e. no dashpot). Then <m>c=0</m> in equation <xref ref="dashpoteqn" text="global" /> above. 
        That is, <m>\displaystyle m\frac{d^{2}x}{dt^{2}}+ kx = 0</m>. Since <m>k, m &gt; 0</m>, 
        define <m>\displaystyle \omega_{0} = \sqrt{\frac{k}{m}}</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Determine a characteristic equation and roots for the resulting DE (when <m>c=0</m>).
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Find a general solution <m>x(t)</m> to the DE.
              Try to state it in terms of <m>\omega_{0}</m> rather than <m>k</m> and <m>m</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        <alert>Undamped Motion.</alert> A body with mass <m>m = \frac{1}{2}</m> kilogram is attached to 
        the end of a spring that is stretched 2 meters by a force of 100 newtons. It is set in motion 
        with initial position <m>x_{0} = 1</m> meter and initial velocity <m>v_{0} = -5</m> meters 
        per second.
      </p>

      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Determine the value of the spring constant <m>k</m> and the resulting DE that guides the 
              motion of the mass.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Describe a DE that governs the motion of the mass.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Describe in words the meaning of these initial conditions.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              With <m>\omega_{0} = 10</m>, the solution to this IVP is 
              <m>\displaystyle x(t) = \cos 10t - \frac{1}{2}\sin 10t</m>.
              This means the mass will oscillate (simple harmonic motion) with <term>frequency</term> 
              <m>\displaystyle \nu = \frac{\omega_{0}}{2\pi}</m> (measured in hertz; cycles per second).
              What is the frequency <m>\nu</m>? What is the <term>period</term> <m>T</m>?
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              A solution in the form <m>x(t) = c_{1}\cos \omega_{0} t + c_{2} \sin \omega_{0} t</m> 
              can be written into the more useful <term>amplitude-phase form</term> 
              <m>x(t) = A \cos (\omega_{0} t - \phi)</m> where the <term>amplitude</term> <m>A>0</m> 
              and the <term>phase shift</term> <m>0 \leq \phi &#x3C; 2\pi</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>A = \sqrt{c_{1}^{2} + c_{2}^{2}}</m>. Determine the value of <m>A</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>\displaystyle \tan \phi = \frac{c_{2}}{c_{1}}</m>. Estimate the value of 
                    <m>\phi</m>. [Careful: <m>\phi</m> is in the fourth quadrant.]
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The first peak in the graph of <m>x(t) = A \cos (\omega_{0} t - \phi)</m> occurs at 
              <m>\displaystyle t^{*} = \frac{\phi}{\omega_{0}}</m> (called the <term>time lag</term>.
              Determine the time lag for the solution to this problem and sketch a graph of the motion 
              <m>x(t)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
   

  <p>
    With <term>damping</term> (<m>c>0</m>), in equation <xref ref="dashpoteqn" text="global" />, we 
    investigate the characteristic roots of <m>mr^{2} + cr + k = 0</m>.
    These are
    <me>
      r = \frac{-c \pm \sqrt{c^{2} - 4mk}}{2m}.
    </me>
    We have three cases:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        <term>Overdamped.</term> <m>c^{2} > 4mk \implies</m> two distinct real roots.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        <term>Critically damped.</term> <m>c^{2} = 4mk \implies</m> one repeated real root.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        <term>Underdamped.</term> <m>c^{2} &#x3C; 4mk \implies</m> two complex conjugate roots.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>

  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      <term>Overdamped Motion.</term> If <m>c^{2} > 4mk</m>, the value of <m>c</m> is relatively 
      large and we are dealing with strong resistance in comparison to a relatively weak spring or 
      a small mass. Note also that
      <me>
        0 &#x3C; \sqrt{c^{2} - 4mk}&#x3C; c.
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            The two (real, distinct) roots <m>r_{1}</m> and <m>r_{2}</m> solve <m>mr^{2} + cr+k=0</m>.
            Explain why these roots are both negative.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Give a general solution <m>x(t)</m> to the DE <m>m\frac{d^{2}x}{dt^{2}}+ c\frac{dx}{dt}+ kx = 0.</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Compute <m>\displaystyle \lim_{t \rightarrow \infty}x(t)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>

    <p>
      <term>Critically Damped Motion.</term> Here, <m>c^{2} = 4mk</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Explain why the one (real, repeated) root to <m>mr^{2} + cr+k=0</m> is <m>\displaystyle r = -\frac{c}{2m}</m>.
            Why this root is negative?
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Give a general solution <m>x(t)</m> to the DE <m>m\frac{d^{2}x}{dt^{2}}+ c\frac{dx}{dt}+ kx = 0.</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Compute <m>\displaystyle \lim_{t \rightarrow \infty}x(t)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>

    <p>
      <term>Underdamped Motion.</term> If <m>c^{2} &#x3C; 4mk</m>, the value of <m>c</m> is 
      relatively small and we are dealing with very little resistance in comparison to a relatively 
      strong spring or a large mass. For example, suppose <m>c=1</m>, <m>m = \frac{1}{2}</m>, and 
      <m>k = 50</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            The roots to the characteristic equation <m>mr^{2} + cr+k=0</m> complex.
            What are they?
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Given initial conditions of <m>x(0)=1</m> and <m>x'(0)=-5</m>, the solution <m>x(t)</m> to the DE <m>m\frac{d^{2}x}{dt^{2}}+ c\frac{dx}{dt}+ kx = 0</m> is
            <me>
              x(t) = e^{-t}\left( \cos \sqrt{99}t - \frac{4}{\sqrt{99}}\sin \sqrt{99}t \right) \approx \sqrt{\frac{115}{99}}e^{-t}\cos \left( \sqrt{99}t - 5.9009 \right).
            </me>
            Compute <m>\displaystyle \lim_{t \rightarrow \infty}x(t)</m>.
            What does the plot of <m>x(t)</m> look like?
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </li>
  </ol>
</li>



</ol>
</li>


